com.axibase.tsd.service.el.series.models

Class Series

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.axibase.tsd.service.el.series.models.Series
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    ImmutableSeries

    public abstract class Series
extends java.lang.Object
    Series consists of SeriesKey and can represent either true time series or double value (scalar in our terms). Time series is stored as a Map: long timestamp -> double value. Scalar is stored as a single sample - double value with special SCALAR_TIMESTAMP. Use method isScalar() to determine which type (time series or scalar) is stored. Methods with prefix "scalar" returns scalar.

      • shift

        public Series shift(int count)
        Return time series with the same set of timestamps, and shifted values.
        Parameters:
        count - Determine how many times and in which direction shift values. Positive if values should be shifted to the right, negative - to the left. Example: shift(1): [(t1, v1), (t2, v2), (t3, v3)] -> [(t1, NaN), (t2, v1), (t3, v2)] shift(-1): [(t1, v1), (t2, v2), (t3, v3)] -> [(t1, v2), (t2, v3), (t3, NaN)]

      • calculateForEach

        public Series calculateForEach(java.lang.String expression)
                        throws java.io.IOException
        For each series sample evaluate expression in the SeriesContext, which contains sample's timestamp, value and index. Interval-related variables of context should not be used in expression.
        Parameters:
        expression - Must return single double number.
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException

      • calculateForEach

        public Series calculateForEach(java.lang.String expression,
                               java.lang.String interval)
                        throws java.io.IOException
        Split series samples into time intervals, and evaluate expression for each sample in each interval.
        For each series sample evaluate expression in the SeriesContext, where appropriate interval and sample related variables are available.
        Parameters:
        expression - Expression must return single number.
        interval - Time interval in ATSD syntax, e.g. '3 day'.
        Returns:
        Time series, with the same set of timestamps as original series.
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException

      • calculate

        public Series calculate(java.lang.String expression)
                 throws java.io.IOException
        Evaluate expression once in the SeriesContext, note that sample or interval related variables of context has no meaning in this case.
        Parameters:
        expression - Must return either single Number, or Map: Long -> Number, or Series.
        Returns:
        If expression is evaluated to Series then return it, otherwise create series from evaluation result with series key equal to key of this series.
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException

      • calculate

        public Series calculate(java.lang.String expression,
                        java.lang.String interval)
                 throws java.io.IOException
        Split series samples into time intervals. For each interval evaluate expression in the SeriesContext, where interval related variables are available. Sample-related variables of the context has no meaning and should not be used in expression.
        Parameters:
        expression - Expression must generate either single number or map of samples Map.
        interval - Time interval, e.g. "15 SECOND".
        Returns:
        If expression is evaluated to a number, then return regular time series, with timestamps equal to beginnings of intervals. Otherwise return series whose samples are produced by expression.
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException
